===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|nl|h₁es|h₂wes|bʰuH}}
From {{inh|nl|dum|sijn}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|sīn}}. The infinitive {{m|nl||zijn}} along with the words {{m|nl|is}} and {{m|nl|zij}} (present indicative and subjunctive) derive ultimately from {{der|nl|ine-pro|*h₁es-||to be}}, which had no separate infinitive in Germanic. The modern infinitive was probably back-formed in late Old Dutch from the first-person plural subjunctive {{m|odt||sīn|we be}}, since this form had become identical to the infinitive in other verbs during the late Old Dutch period. Compare also German {{m|de|sein}}, Low German {{m|nds|sien}}.

The original infinitive survives in {{m|nl|wezen}}, from {{inh|nl|dum|wesen}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|wesan}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*wesaną}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*h₂wes-||to reside}}. All the forms with initial ''w-'' (imperative and past tense) derive from this root.

Finally, the forms {{m|nl|ben}} and {{m|nl|bent}} derive from {{der|nl|gem-pro|*beuną||to be, to become}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*bʰuH-||to become}}, which survives only as relic forms in the West Germanic languages and not at all in the others. Its infinitive and non-singular forms are only attested in (Old) English.

