===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|nl|dum|sijn}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|sīn}} (originally a reflexive form), from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*sīnaz}}, from {{der|nl|ine-pro|*seyno-}}. Cognate with German {{m|de|sein}}, Swedish {{m|sv|sin}}. Ultimately a form of the Proto-Indo-European reflexive pronoun {{m|ine-pro|*swe}}, related to Russian {{m|ru|себя}}, Latin {{m|la|suus}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|ἑός}} etc.

